            courses: 'MEIC-A, MEIC-T',
            observations: 'Tese atribuida à aluna Rita Ramos',
            objectives: 'Collecting data in natural environments, such as forests and crop fields, is an important task\nthat provides a better insight into the environment, and has many useful applications, for\ninstance wildlife tracking, pest monitoring, and fire detection. Collecting environmental data is\nsuitable to be carried out by a large number of sensor networks or a swarm of robots, since they\nallow for distributed sensing, scalability, and robustness to faults, which is necessary to perform\nthis type of tasks. Sensors networks have been widely used for different types of applications,\nincluding environmental monitoring. Despite the interesting work done so far, static sensor\nnetworks are limited by their inability to change their spatial configuration, whereas the\nmobility of robots enables the collection of data from a changing set of locations that can be\nadapted on the fly. As opposed to static sensors, mobile robots have the capacity to self-organize\nand maximize the coverage area of interest. In respect to the mobility required in unstructured\nenvironments, it could be argued that flying over rough terrain is the most efficient approach,\nbut flying robots can be a drawback for applications that require a close exploration to the\nground, and, flying robots are also too energetically expensive to perform data collection\nmissions of long term. Wheeled robots are often not suited for rough terrain, they are unable to\nnegotiate obstacles that are larger than half of the wheel diameter. While legged robots may able\nto navigate such terrains, the mechanical complexity necessary to realize legged locomotion in\nrough terrain is so high that the resulting robots tend to be expensive. Jumping is a promising\nalternative means of locomotion since it allows for navigation in unstructured environments,\nwhile at the same time can be kept relatively simple mechanically and therefore inexpensive.\nFurthermore, jumping has high energy efficiency and locomotion efficacy, which establishes that\njumping robotic systems have a potential for carrying out real-world tasks in natural and\nunstructured environments.\nIn this project, we are interested in studying collective intelligent behaviours for a swarm of\njumping robots to environmental monitoring. A major aspect to perform such type of tasks\nconcerns the battery of the robots. Most current robots do not carry enough energy to perform\nmissions of long duration. Therefore, in this project, we aim to build a swarm of jumping robots\nthat have the ability to recharge themselves in the field, for instance by means of solar panels. A\nmain challenge involved is how robots will manage the tradeoff between performing the mission\nand finding suitable spots to harvest energy such as a spot with sunlight.\nWe will apply evolutionary techniques to synthesize neural controllers for the robots.\nEvolutionary Robotics (ER) is a field in which controllers for autonomous robots are synthesized\nby means of evolutionary computation techniques without the need for manual and detailed\nspecification of behavior. In particular, in the master thesis, we will focus in evolving flocking\nbehaviour for robots operating in natural unstructured environments for long durations. Among\nthe various advantages of flocking, many biology studies have shown that individuals find food\nfaster in a foraging group than on its own. This advantage could be particularly useful in fire\npatrolling, since moving in group has the potential of increasing the chance of locating an\nunknown goal, in this case fire.',
