            objectives: 'The digital game medium has been pushing storytelling through interaction with the world and its characters in detriment to non-interactive exposition. Following this trend, and rather than presenting a cut-scene depicting the interaction between the player and his or her companion to &quot;advance the story&quot; as well as to better characterise non-player characters, in this work, we will create a personality-based interaction model of both players and non-player characters that will decide when to reveal story beats during gameplay or actively create these moments to allow for the story to develop.\n\nThe challenge here is to merge both storytelling and gameplay into one unique continuum and make sure that both dimensions are equally apprehended by the player. Different players will learn about a same part of the story at different moments of the gameplay, and this non-linear resequencing based on &quot;reader&quot; response theory will elicit different experiences while still being coherent as a whole. The idea is to develop a conceptual approach to this storytelling paradigm, develop an example scenario in the Starcraft 2 editor from Blizzard Entertainment (or another game/editor of the student preference) and perform user studies evaluating the adequacy of the approach.\n\nMain sub-goals:\n( 1 ) Literature review (semester 1)\n( 2 ) Computational model (semester 1 and 2)\n( 3 ) Test scenario implementation (semester 2)\n( 4 ) User studies (semester 2)',
